result.execSummary:
The defendant James L Pardee was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Criminal Trespass to Dwelling, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.14.
  • Criminal Damage to Property, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.01(1).
  • Criminal Damage to Property, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.01(1).
  • Intimidate Victim/Threaten Force, etc., a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.45(3).
  • Intimidate Witness/Use or Attempt Force, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.43(1).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: To commit no further criminal acts during the period of the agreement. No contact with S.H. with exception of the apology letter. To consume no alcoholic beverages or controlled substances. No entry into bars or taverns. Not to possess drug paraphernalia.

Defendant shall provide a copy of this agreement, along with the Criminal Complaint, to any counselor and sign any and all releases necessary to allow the counselor (or agency) to report compliance or lack thereof to the District Attorney's Office.  Any assessments done without this agreement and the Criminal Complaint(s) being supplied to the counselor will be considered violations of this agreement and not be accepted.  This agreement may be revoked or the defendant may have to complete a new assessment. Defendant shall comply with any and all rules of probation and successfully complete any term of probation ordered as part of this case. Defendant will, on or before, 30 days of the agreement, send written letters of apology to S.H. and Officer Dorner, of not less than 300 words each, to the defendant's probation agent. Upon approval, probation agent will forward letter to the victims.

Defendant James L Pardee in court with attorney David R. Clowers.  Defendant James L Pardee in custody.  Raymond Pelrine appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Minute sheet. State amends Ct. 8 to Misd. Bail Jumping, gives plea agreement.  Court questions defendant on change of plea.  Rights/elements/max. penalties reviewed with defendant.  Defendant enters no contest plea to Cts. 1, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7 & 8. Defense stipulates to factual basis to accept plea.  Court finds pleas made freely, knowingly and voluntarily, accepts pleas, and finds guilty of Cts. 1, 3, 4, 5 & 8. Court withholds accepting of the plea on Cts. 6 & 7 to allow defendant time to complete term of the Deferred Acceptance of Guilty Plea Agreement. Court dismisses Ct. 2 but reads in for sentencing. Defendant must have a DNA sample on file with the State of Wisconsin and pay a DNA surcharge. Court reviews collateral consequences with defendant should he be found guilty of a felony. Upon successful completion of DAGPA, State will move, after 3 years, to dismiss Cts. 6 & 7.  Court reviews Deferred Acceptance of Guilty Plea Agreement with defendant, approves and signs agreement. State moves to amend cash bond to a signature bond with same conditions. Court grants request.  Deferred prosecution agreement hearing scheduled for November 29, 2018 at 11:45 am.

Atty Clowers asks court to reduce cash bond to $2,500, makes statement on bond modification. State objects to bond modification, makes statement. Atty Clowers responds to State's argument.  Court makes statement, denies request to reduce cash bond. Bond remains in effect as previously set.
